A client wrote this in their food + mood journal the other day and I’ve been thinking about it ever sense…

“Don’t take criticism from someone you wouldn’t take advice from”

🗣️🗣️🗣️

It’s so true. And so good. 

How often are you quick to soak in negative feedback or comments from people (strangers, friends, family, etc) but then recognize they probably aren’t someone you’d go to for advice or support

Sure, this is way easier said than done!

But how do you think your day would look if you walked in that truth?

#mindfulnesspractice #bodyrespect #nutritiontherapy #nondietapproach #bodyconfidencemovement #dietsdontwork #newyearsresolution #mindsetmatters #wellnesswithoutobsession

Let’s chat feeling out of control around sugar 👇🏼 

Have you ever felt you might be “addicted” to sugar?

If you’ve felt that way… I want you to think about if you’ve also felt you need to limit, restrict and/or avoid sugar

Because what we know to be true is avoiding foods leads us to crave it more

When we tell ourselves we can’t have something, we want it even more…

In fact, there was research study done where children were told they couldn’t eat the red M+M, but they could eat as many yellow M+Ms as they wanted

So they could have the same candy, just a different color

Guess which one got eaten the most? 

RED

Because restricting foods leads to increased cravings time and time again 
There’s quite a bit of research to support this - the more you tell yourself (or someone tells you) not to have something, the more you want and crave it. This can often lead to overeating

Inside FREE Method: Academy (our group coaching program), we teach our members the power pick strategy to building balanced meals so they can have peace of mind around all food decisions.

In fact, Katie, one of our past members, said that date nights with her husband are BETTER than ever since learning the power pick strategy.

When you challenge diet rules or eating disorder beliefs, it’s normal to feel uncomfortable 

That discomfort may lead you wanting to run back to what feels “safe”… your eating disorder or a diet

It’s likely those behaviors have kept you safe from a lot!

But what if the thing that is keeping you safe, is actually keep you sick!?

That is where this idea of riding the wave comes into play…

You are tempted to engage in a behavior that you have identified is not aligned with recovery

And you’ve identified you want to walk away from said behavior

HELLO distressss

I want you to envision a wave… as the wave develops, the height of the wave rises and then it settles back down

Your emotions can operate in that same pattern, but it’s easy for us to try and jump off the wave by running to whatever behavior(s) help us avoid those emotions

So as we work to ride the wave, bringing in tools to help you tolerate that distress is key!

Need more support in this journey?

We’d love to help you! Schedule a free discovery call to chat more - freemethodnutrition.com/freecall

As the Nashville community, a place I call home, is experiencing unimaginable tragedy, I want to remind y'all of several ways to support your body and nervous system in times of tragedy and grief.

Processing tragedy and grief looks different for everyone, and it's really easy to neglect your own needs when your body is on high-alert and in fight-or-flight mode.

Your appetite is quick to go in seasons of grief, anxiety and depression. Keep food simple, set reminders on your phone for meals, lean into foods that bring your comfort and peace.

🤍🤍🤍

The amount of times I heard this phrase in the first few months postpartum with Caulder was insane...

As women who chose to and/or are able to bear children, we sacrifice our bodies for 9+ months, birth a human being (which honestly we all deserve a gold medal for that) and then have tear-filled, sleep-deprived days trying to adjust to a newborn and the onlyyyyy "compliment" that comes to mind is "you don't even look like you had a baby" or "wow, you look so good"

Can we all stop with that? Please.

I promise there are so many other kind, heart-felt things we can say to new moms. 

And I'm sure if you have said this phrase before, you probably meant well but let me give you some other things to say instead.

"What can I do to help?"
"I'm so proud of you!"
"You're such a good mom!"

Because I think most moms would agree, I hope I look like I had a baby

Moms - what are some other compliments that a new mom may appreciate?

There may be a way your workouts can be a tool to nourish your body instead of punish it…

Oftentimes, exercise is rooted out of dissatisfaction in your body. Forcing yourself to move in a way that isn’t empowering or enjoyable. 

Movement doesn’t have to be that way. 

Yes, you can challenge yourself. Yes, you can want to build muscle, do more push ups, run farther, etc etc. 

But the CLEAR difference is the motivation and voice behind that. 

Is your decision to exercise rooted in self care or self hate?

Because I can promise you, if it’s the latter you won’t get all the amazing benefits movement has to offer. 

What you will also find is you’ll have the clarity to decide how you actually enjoy moving your body!

Maybe it’s running or Pilates or hip hop classes or weight training in the gym. 

The what doesn’t really matter, the why is what does!

So ask yourself - why do I exercise?

Feeding your littles can be hard, I get it. 

Trust me - I’m in the thick of it.

BUT, it doesn’t have to be as hard as we make it.

Here are 3 tips to make feeding your littles easier (and raise them as intuitive eaters)

1. Make meals fun - let them bring their favorite toy or eat with a cocktail spoon. 

2. Keep reintroducing foods - they don’t like veggies? Continue to put them on their plate but don’t make a big deal about it. They may not eat veggies for a while and that’s okay (and maybe that’s what pouches are for, am I right!?)

3. Sit with your kids while they eat - even better if you are eating too! They learn so much from watching you, and there is endless evidence on the importance of family meals

ALSO - as you are feeding your littles, it is SO important to check your own food beliefs and rules. 

Feeling like a “bad mom” because your little won’t touch veggies?

Embarrassed that your child is surviving off bars and pouches?

Trying to avoid giving your kids dessert or added sugar?

If any of those feel like you, I encourage you to do some digging to see where those beliefs and thoughts are coming from. 

May be a sign that you have some inner work to do yourself - and that’s OKAY!

We would love to help! Many of our dietitians are fellow moms figuring out this right alongside you, so we are happy to help you work on your own relationship with food so you can best serve your kids!

Been keeping a little secret over here the past 9 months 💕 Margaret “Rivers” Murphy made a speedy arrival yesterday  morning and we are soaking up every ounce of our little girlie!
Still in the thick of newborn days with a toddler over here, but we’ve made it two weeks with our Rivers girlie and that feels like an accomplishment worth celebrating 🤍

My feeding journey with Rivers has been quite a whirlwind, and we are still learning and figuring it all out but a few things I’ve realized so far this time around:

🍼 Prioritizing my own mental health as I navigating feeding Rivers is hard, especially in a world that screams “breast is best” and makes formula seem like dirt off the ground

🍼 When we talk about what type of feeding is best, the “who” it is best for should include the mom just as much as the baby. I’ve always looked at it through the lens of what is best for the baby, and while yes that is obviously important, we have to factor the mom into that equation too

🍼 Whether nursing, pumping, formula, or all the above, feeding a tiny human is hard work and moms (and any parent) should be supported not judged on how they choose to/are able to feed their baby

One thing I’m SO thankful for in my feeding journey with Rivers is @bobbie, I love that it’s Mom-founded and led and is filled with key nutrients found in breast milk - giving me peace of mind that Rivers is getting the complete nutrition she needs 🤍
